---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";

const features = [
  { href: "/docs/architecture/", title: "Runtime core", body: "Own turns, cancellation, tool execution, policy, event ordering, and replay in one typed Rust loop." },
  { href: "/docs/extensibility/", title: "Replaceable subsystems", body: "Swap providers, memory, storage, policy, remote runners, event sinks, and UI surfaces through native extensions." },
  { href: "/docs/providers/", title: "Provider-neutral inference", body: "Map OpenAI, Anthropic, Gemini, OpenRouter, Cursor, chat-completions engines, and embedding providers into canonical Roder types." },
  { href: "/docs/app-server/", title: "One control plane", body: "Drive the TUI, desktop clients, automation, Chrome control, and sandbox-hosted workers through the same app-server protocol." },
  { href: "/docs/tools/", title: "Scoped tool use", body: "Route tools through explicit specs, approval events, policy modes, scoped handles, and deadline-aware command limits." },
  { href: "/docs/workflows/", title: "Repeatable workflows", body: "Run approval-gated scripts that plan phases, spawn child agents, checkpoint progress, and report structured results." },
  { href: "/evals/", title: "Eval trajectory", body: "Track Harbor and Terminal-Bench results with full-suite scores, targeted reruns, and reproducible artifacts." },
  { href: "/docs/zerolang/", title: "Domain distributions", body: "Build task-specific agents such as the Zerolang profile without forking the runtime." },
];

const audiences = [
  { title: "Agent product teams", body: "Build a differentiated UI and workflow on top of a runtime you do not have to reinvent." },
  { title: "AI labs and eval teams", body: "Collect structured trajectories, replay runs, compare providers, and control tool access." },
  { title: "Platform engineers", body: "Embed a coding-agent runtime behind internal tools, CI jobs, desktop clients, or hosted sandboxes." },
];
---

<Layout
  title="Roder · reusable runtime infrastructure for coding agents"
  description="Roder is a Rust runtime for teams building, evaluating, and embedding coding agents that need real tools, policy, state, and replay."
>
  <section class="container">
    <div class="hero">
      <div class="hero-copy">
        <div class="eyebrow-line">Rust runtime infrastructure for coding agents</div>
        <h1 class="wordmark">Roder</h1>
        <p class="tagline">
          Build coding agents that can run real jobs: tools, policy, state, events,
          replay, providers, and clients all handled by one extensible runtime.
        </p>
        <div class="cta-row">
          <a class="btn btn-primary" href="/docs/">Read the docs</a>
          <a class="btn btn-primary" href="/contact/">Talk to the team</a>
          <a class="btn btn-secondary" href="/evals/">See evals</a>
          <a class="btn btn-secondary" href="/docs/install/">Run it locally</a>
          <a class="btn btn-secondary" href="/mission/">Read the mission</a>
        </div>
      </div>
      <img class="logo" src="/roder-icon.png" alt="Roder icon" />
    </div>

    <div class="feature-strip" aria-label="Roder architecture summary">
      <div class="metric"><strong>Runtime</strong><span>turns, tools, policy, cancellation</span></div>
      <div class="metric"><strong>State</strong><span>sessions, checkpoints, replay, traces</span></div>
      <div class="metric"><strong>Extensions</strong><span>providers, memory, runners, UI</span></div>
      <div class="metric"><strong>Control</strong><span>TUI, desktop, automation, sandboxes</span></div>
    </div>

    <pre><code>$ cargo build --workspace
$ cargo test -p roder-cli
$ cargo run -p roder-cli
$ cargo run -p roder-cli -- app-server</code></pre>

    <h2>What Roder is</h2>
    <p>
      Roder is the runtime layer underneath serious coding-agent systems. It is not trying
      to be one more sealed chat app. It gives product teams, labs, and platform engineers
      the reusable machinery they all end up building: model orchestration, tool execution,
      permission boundaries, context assembly, session state, checkpointing, event streams,
      and replay.
    </p>
    <p>
      The core bet is simple: the hard parts of running an agent should become shared
      infrastructure. Teams should compete on models, UX, workflows, tools, and domain
      knowledge instead of rebuilding the same harness every time they need a new product
      surface or evaluation loop.
    </p>

    <div class="callout">
      <strong>Alpha software.</strong> Roder is useful to explore and build with today, but
      core types, extension traits, commands, protocol methods, and config keys are still
      moving. Treat the docs and crate boundaries as the working contract until a stable
      API is declared.
    </div>

    <h2>Who it is for</h2>
    <div class="features">
      {audiences.map((audience) => (
        <div class="feature-card">
          <h3>{audience.title}</h3>
          <p>{audience.body}</p>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>

    <h2>Explore</h2>
    <div class="features">
      {features.map((f) => (
        <a class="feature-card" href={f.href}>
          <h3>{f.title}</h3>
          <p>{f.body}</p>
        </a>
      ))}
    </div>

    <h2>Core bet</h2>
    <p>
      Agent systems should not keep rebuilding scaffolding around every model API. Roder
      makes conversations, turns, tool calls, inference events, file changes, policy
      decisions, sessions, and checkpoints canonical Rust concepts. Extensions translate
      into that model, so new providers, workflows, sandboxes, and domain tools can plug in
      without taking over the runtime.
    </p>

    <div class="callout">
      <strong>Building on this problem?</strong> The Roder team works with AI labs and
      startups on embedded harnesses, RL and eval infrastructure, product integrations, and
      OSS sponsorship. <a href="/contact/">Start a conversation</a>.
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
